instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "Architecture is derived from ISO 23247 Reference Architecture, mapping software components to functional entities and deploying each entity on separate hardware. Functional entities are organized into ROS 2 packages, with each package containing ROS 2 nodes implementing the FE’s responsibilities. The Digital Twin Entity aggregates data management and control modules, while the Physical Twin Entity encapsulates vehicle resources and general automotive functions such as point‑cloud clustering/tracking. The User Entity contains visualization and control panel sub‑components. System‑wide coordination is achieved via ROS 2 middleware, enabling inter‑entity messaging, shared data topics, and service calls."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "All software components of the Digital Twin Service (DTS) are connected over an internal ROS 2 network that uses the Data Distribution Service (DDS) as transport layer, enabling low‑latency intra‑computer communication. Cross‑entity communication, i.e., between the vehicle’s physical twin and the DTS running on the cloud/edge cluster, is performed over Wi‑Fi using UDP sockets, as specified for the inter‑entity link in ISO 23247. The Data Translation FE serialises messages and executes unit conversion before the packets are sent over UDP. The network topology thus consists of (i) a micro‑service mesh of ROS 2 nodes on the edge computer, (ii) a Wi‑Fi gateway that bridges to the DTS central node, and (iii) optionally a redundant second wireless link for reliability. Bandwidth requirements are dictated by the LiDAR stream: transmitting high‑resolution point‑clouds (≈ 30 MB/s at 20 Hz) and vehicle state updates (≈ 200 kbps). Latency tolerance for real‑time monitoring is ≤ 50 ms, while control commands from the virtual twin are required to be delivered within 10 ms. Reliability is enhanced by UDP checksum verification, packet sequence numbers, and automatic retransmission requests for critical control messages."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "Complies with ISO 23247 – Digital Twin Framework for Manufacturing (parts 1‑4). Employs the entity‑based reference architecture comprising the Observable Manufacturing Element (OME), Data Collection and Device Control Entity, Digital Twin Entity and User Entity. Functional Entities (FEs) are defined for specific tasks such as actuating the OME, data transformation and user interaction. Communication between FEs may be implemented using OPC Unified Architecture (OPC UA) as an explicit example, thereby ensuring interoperability with industrial automation systems."
]
